# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: airfoil
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Most aerobatic maneuvers involve rotation of the aircraft about its longitudinal (roll) axis or lateral (pitch) axis.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Other maneuvers, such as a spin, displace the aircraft about its vertical (yaw) axis.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Manoeuvres are often combined to form a complete aerobatic sequence for entertainment or competition.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatic flying requires a broader set of piloting skills and exposes the aircraft to greater structural stress than for normal flight.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] In some countries, the pilot must wear a parachute when performing aerobatics.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatic training enhances a pilot's ability to recover from unusual flight conditions, and thus is an element of many flight safety training programs for pilots.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] While many pilots fly aerobatics for recreation, some choose to fly in aerobatic competitions, a judged sport.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] In the early days of flying, some pilots used their aircraft as part of a flying circus to entertain.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Maneuvers were flown for artistic reasons or to draw gasps from onlookers.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] In due course some of these maneuvers were found to allow aircraft to gain tactical advantage during aerial combat or dogfights between fighter aircraft.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatic aircraft fall into two categories—specialist aerobatic, and aerobatic capable.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Specialist designs such as the Pitts Special, the Extra 200 and 300, and the Sukhoi Su-26M and Sukhoi Su-29 aim for ultimate aerobatic performance.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] This comes at the expense of general purpose use such as touring, or ease of non aerobatic handling such as landing.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] At a more basic level, *aerobatic capable* aircraft, such as the Cessna 152 Aerobat or the R2160 Acrobin, can be dual purpose—equipped to carrying passengers and luggage, as well as being capable of basic aerobatic figures.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatic maneuvers flown in a jet-powered aircraft are limited in scope as they cannot take advantage of the gyroscopic forces that a propeller driven aircraft can exploit.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Jet-powered aircraft also tend to fly much faster, which increases the size of the figures and the length of time the pilot has to withstand increased g-forces.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Jet aerobatic teams often fly in formations, which further restricts the maneuvers that can be safely flown.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatics done at low levels and for an audience is called "stunt flying".
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] To enhance the show effect of aerobatic manoeuvres, smoke is sometimes generated; the smoke allows viewers to see the path travelled by the aircraft.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Due to safety concerns, the smoke is not a result of combustion but is produced by the vaporization of fog oil into a fine aerosol, achieved either by injecting the oil into the hot engine exhaust or by the use of a dedicated device that can be fitted in any position on the aircraft.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] The first military aerobatic team to use smoke at will during displays was Fleet Air Arm 702 Squadron "The Black Cats" at the Farnborough Airshow in September 1957.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatics are typically performed in aeroplanes and gliders, but are not limited solely to fixed-wing aircraft, as they can also be performed in specific helicopters, such as the MBB Bo 105, Westland Lynx and Eurocopter EC120 Colibri.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] The British Army, Royal Navy, Spanish Air Force and the Indian Air Force have helicopter display teams.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatics are taught to military fighter pilots as a means of developing flying skills and for tactical use in combat.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Many aerobatic manoeuvres were indeed developed in military conflicts, e.g. the Immelmann turn or Split S.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatics demands extensive training and practice to avoid accidents.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Accidents due to aerobatic manoeuvres are very rare in competition aerobatics; most of them happen when performing formation flying or stunt flying at very low levels at airshows or air racing.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Low-level aerobatics are extremely demanding and airshow pilots must demonstrate their ability before being allowed to gradually reduce the height at which they may fly their show.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] In the European Union, aerobatics requires special training and a rating.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] In Canada, no licence is required to perform aerobatics, but to carry passengers during aerobatics a pilot must have at least 10 hours dual flight instruction of aerobatic manoeuvres, or 20 hours of total aerobatic experience.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatic flying competitions are a worldwide phenomenon, rather like the Olympic games, and are governed by the FAI Aerobatics Commission (CIVA).
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Competitions start at Primary, or Graduate level (in UK "Beginners") and proceed in complexity through Sportsman (in UK "Standard"), Intermediate and Advanced, with Unlimited being the top competition level.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Experienced aerobatic pilots have been measured to pull ±5 g for short periods while unlimited pilots can perform more extreme maneuvers and experience higher g levels -possibly up to +8/−6 g.
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] The limits for positive g are higher than for negative g and this is due to the ability to limit blood pooling for positive g maneuvers, but it is generally accepted that +9 g for more than a few seconds will lead to loss of consciousness (also known as GLOC).
[src:airfoil/aerobatic] Aerobatics are likely to be seen at public airshows in the form of stunt flying.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] The **aerodynamic center** is the point at which the pitching moment coefficient for the airfoil does not vary with lift coefficient (i.e. angle of attack), making analysis simpler.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] The lift and drag forces can be applied at a single point, the center of pressure.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] However, the location of the center of pressure moves significantly with a change in angle of attack and is thus impractical for aerodynamic analysis.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] Instead the aerodynamic center is used and as a result the incremental lift and drag due to change in angle of attack acting at this point is sufficient to describe the aerodynamic forces acting on the given body.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] Within the assumptions embodied in thin airfoil theory, the aerodynamic center is located at the quarter-chord (25% chord position) on a symmetric airfoil while it is close but not exactly equal to the quarter-chord point on a cambered airfoil.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] For symmetrical airfoils $\ m_{0}=0$ , so the aerodynamic center is at 25% of chord measured from the leading edge.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] But for cambered airfoils the aerodynamic center can be slightly less than 25% of the chord from the leading edge, which depends on the slope of the moment coefficient, $\ m_{0}$ .
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] These results obtained are calculated using the thin airfoil theory so the use of the results are warranted only when the assumptions of thin airfoil theory are realistic.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] In precision experimentation with real airfoils and advanced analysis, the aerodynamic center is observed to change location slightly as angle of attack varies.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-center] In most literature however the aerodynamic center is assumed to be fixed at the 25% chord position.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-force] In fluid mechanics, an **aerodynamic force** is a force exerted on a body by the air (or other gas) in which the body is immersed, and is due to the relative motion between the body and the gas.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-force] Pressure acts normal to the surface, and shear force acts parallel to the surface.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-force] The net aerodynamic force on the body is equal to the pressure and shear forces integrated over the body's total exposed area.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-force] When an airfoil moves relative to the air, it generates an aerodynamic force determined by the velocity of relative motion, and the angle of attack.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-force] In addition to these two forces, the body may experience an aerodynamic moment.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-force] The force created by propellers and jet engines is called *thrust*, and is a reaction force.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamic-force] The other force acting on an aircraft is its weight, which is a body force and not an aerodynamic force.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:airfoil/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:airfoil/ailerons] An **aileron** (French for 'little wing' or 'fin') is a hinged flight control surface usually forming part of the trailing edge of each wing of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Ailerons are used in pairs to control the aircraft in roll (or movement around the aircraft's longitudinal axis), which normally results in a change in flight path due to the tilting of the lift vector.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Movement around this axis is called rolling or banking.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Considerable controversy exists over credit for the invention of the aileron.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The Wright brothers and Glenn Curtiss fought a years-long legal battle over the Wright patent of 1906, which described a method of wing-warping to achieve lateral control.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The brothers prevailed in several court decisions which found that Curtiss's use of ailerons violated the Wright patent.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Ultimately, the First World War compelled the U.S.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Government to legislate a legal resolution.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] A much earlier aileron concept was patented in 1868 by British scientist Matthew Piers Watt Boulton, based on his 1864 paper *On Aërial Locomotion*.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The name "aileron", from French, meaning "little wing", also refers to the extremities of a bird's wings used to control their flight.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] It first appeared in print in the 7th edition of Cassell's French-English Dictionary of 1877, with its lead meaning of "small wing".
[src:airfoil/ailerons] In the context of powered airplanes it appears in print about 1908.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Prior to that, ailerons were often referred to as rudders, their older technical sibling, with no distinction between their orientations and functions, or more descriptively as *horizontal rudders* (in French, *gouvernails horizontaux*).
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Among the earliest printed aeronautical use of 'aileron' was that in the French aviation journal *L'Aérophile* of 1908.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Ailerons had more or less completely supplanted other forms of lateral control, such as wing warping, by about 1915, well after the function of the rudder and elevator flight controls had been largely standardised.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] He was the first to patent an aileron control system in 1868.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Boulton's description of his lateral flight control system was "the first record we have of appreciation of the necessity for active lateral control as distinguished from [passive lateral stability]....
[src:airfoil/ailerons] With this invention of Boulton's we have the birth of the present-day three torque method of airborne control" as was praised by Charles Manly.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] 392 of 1868, issued about 35 years before ailerons were "reinvented" in France, became forgotten and lost from sight until after the flight control device was in general use.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Gibbs-Smith stated on several occasions that if the Boulton patent had been revealed at the time of the Wright brothers' legal filings, they might not have been able to claim priority of invention for the lateral control of flying machines.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The fact that the Wright brothers were able to gain a patent in 1906 did not invalidate Boulton's lost and forgotten invention.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The pioneering U.S. aeronautical engineer Octave Chanute published descriptions and drawings of the Wright brothers' 1902 glider in the leading aviation periodical of the day, *L'Aérophile*, in 1903.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This prompted Esnault-Pelterie, a French military engineer, to build a Wright-style glider in 1904 that used ailerons in lieu of wing warping.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The French journal *L'Aérophile* then published photos of the ailerons on Esnault-Pelterie's glider which were included in his June 1905 article, and its ailerons were widely copied afterward.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The Wright brothers used wing warping instead of ailerons for roll control on their glider in 1902, and about 1904 their Flyer II was the only aircraft of its time able to do a coordinated banked turn.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] During the early years of powered flight the Wrights had better roll control on their designs than airplanes that used movable surfaces.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] From 1908, as aileron designs were refined it became clear that ailerons were much more effective and practical than wing warping.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Ailerons also had the advantage of not weakening the airplane's wing structure as did the wing warping technique, which was one reason for Esnault-Pelterie's decision to switch to ailerons.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] By 1911, most biplanes used ailerons rather than wing warping—by 1915, ailerons had become almost universal on monoplanes as well.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Government, frustrated by the lack of its country's aeronautical advances in the years leading up to World War I, enforced a patent pool effectively putting an end to the Wright brothers patent war.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The Wright company quietly changed its aircraft flight controls from wing warping to the use of ailerons at that time as well.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The Wright Brothers' Ohio patent attorney Henry Toulmin filed an expansive patent application and on May 22, 1906, the brothers were granted U.S.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The patent's importance lay in its claim of a new and useful method of *controlling* an airplane.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The patent application included the claim for the lateral control of aircraft flight that was not limited to wing warping, but through any manipulation of the "....angular relations of the lateral margins of the airplanes [wings].... varied in opposite directions".
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Thus the patent explicitly stated that other methods besides wing-warping could be used for adjusting the outer portions of an airplane's wings to different angles on its right and left sides to achieve lateral roll control.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Patent 831173 at nearly the same time for his methods of wing warping.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Both the Wright Brothers patent and Montgomery's patent were reviewed and approved by the same patent examiner at the United States Patent Office, William Townsend.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] At the time Townsend indicated that both methods of wing warping were invented independently and were sufficiently different to each justify their own patent award.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Multiple U.S. court decisions favoured the expansive Wright patent, which the Wright Brothers sought to enforce with licensing fees starting from $1,000 per airplane, and said to range up to $1,000 per day.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Casey, a former curator of the Smithsonian Air & Space Museum in Washington, D.C., and other researchers, due to the patent they had received the Wrights stood firmly on the position that all flying using lateral roll control, anywhere in the world, would only be conducted under license by them.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Years of protracted legal conflict ensued with many other aircraft builders until the U.S. entered World War I, when the government imposed a legislated agreement among the parties which resulted in royalty payments of 1% to the Wrights.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] There are still conflicting claims today over who first invented the aileron.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Other 19th century engineers and scientists, including Charles Renard, Alphonse Pénaud, and Louis Mouillard, had described similar flight control surfaces.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Another technique for lateral flight control, wing warping, was also described or experimented with by several people including Jean-Marie Le Bris, John Montgomery, Clement Ader, Edson Gallaudet, D.D.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Gibbs-Smith wrote that the aileron was "....one of the most remarkable inventions... of aeronautical history, which was immediately lost sight of".
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Ailerons are usually situated near the wing tip, but may sometimes also be situated nearer the wing root.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Modern airliners may also have a second pair of ailerons on their wings, with the two positions distinguished by the terms "outboard aileron" and "inboard aileron".
[src:airfoil/ailerons] An unwanted side effect of aileron operation is adverse yaw, a yawing moment in the opposite direction to the roll.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Using the ailerons to roll an aircraft to the right produces a yawing motion to the left.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] As the aircraft rolls, adverse yaw is caused partly by the change in drag between the left and right wing.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The rising wing generates increased lift, which causes increased induced drag.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The descending wing generates reduced lift, which causes reduced induced drag.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Profile drag caused by the deflected ailerons may add further to the difference, along with changes in the lift vectors as one rotates back while the other rotates forward.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] In a coordinated turn, adverse yaw is effectively compensated by the use of the rudder, which results in a sideforce on the vertical tail that opposes the adverse yaw by creating a favorable yawing moment.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Another method of compensation is "differential ailerons", which have been rigged so that the down-going aileron deflects less than the up-going one.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] In this case the opposing yaw moment is generated by a difference in profile drag between the left and right wingtips.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Ailerons may also be designed to use a combination of these methods.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] With ailerons in the neutral position, the wing on the outside of the turn develops more lift than the opposite wing due to the variation in airspeed across the wing span, which tends to cause the aircraft to continue to roll.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Once the desired angle of bank (degree of rotation about the longitudinal axis) has been obtained, the pilot uses opposite aileron to prevent the angle of bank from increasing due to this variation in lift across the wing span.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This minor opposite use of the control must be maintained throughout the turn.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The pilot also uses a slight amount of rudder in the same direction as the turn to counteract adverse yaw and to produce a "coordinated" turn wherein the fuselage is parallel to the flight path.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] A simple gauge on the instrument panel called the slip indicator, also known as "the ball", indicates when this coordination is achieved.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Particularly on larger or faster aircraft, control forces may be extremely heavy.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Borrowing a discovery from boats that extending a control surface's area forward of the hinge lightens the forces needed first appeared on ailerons during World War I when ailerons were extended beyond the wingtip and provided with a horn ahead of the hinge.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Known as overhung ailerons, possibly the best known examples are the Handley Page Type O (first flight 17 December 1915), Sopwith Snipe, Fokker Dr.I and Fokker D.VII.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Later examples brought the counterbalance in line with the wing to improve control and reduce drag.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This is seen less often now, due to the Frise type aileron which provides the same benefit.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Trim tabs are small movable sections resembling scaled down ailerons located at or near the trailing edge of the aileron.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] On most propeller powered aircraft, the rotation of the propellers induces a counteracting roll movement due to Newton's third law of motion, in that every action has an equal and opposite reaction.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] To relieve the pilot of having to provide continuous pressure on the stick in one direction, which causes fatigue, trim tabs are provided to adjust or *trim out* the pressure needed against any unwanted movement.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The tab itself is deflected in relation to the aileron, causing the aileron to move in the opposite direction.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Trim tabs come in two forms, adjustable and fixed.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] A fixed trim tab is manually bent to the required amount of deflection, while the adjustable trim tab can be controlled from within the cockpit so that different power settings or flight attitudes can be compensated for.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Some large aircraft from the 1950s (including the Canadair Argus) used free floating control surfaces that the pilot controlled only through the deflection of trim tabs, in which case additional tabs were also provided to fine-tune the control to provide straight and level flight.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Spades are flat metal plates, usually attached to the aileron lower surface, ahead of the aileron hinge, by a lever arm.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] They reduce the force needed by the pilot to deflect the aileron and are often seen on aerobatic aircraft.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] As the aileron is deflected upward, the spade produces a downward aerodynamic force, which tends to rotate the whole assembly so as to further deflect the aileron upward.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The size of the spade (and its lever arm) determines how much force the pilot needs to apply to deflect the aileron.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] A spade works in the same manner as a horn but is more effective due to the longer moment arm.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] To increase the speed at which control surface flutter (aeroelastic flutter) might become a risk, the center of gravity of the control surface is moved towards the hinge-line for that surface.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] To achieve this, lead weights may be added to the front of the aileron.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] In some aircraft the aileron construction may be too heavy to allow this system to work without an excessive increase in the weight of the aileron.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] In this case, the weight may be added to a lever arm to move the weight well out in front to the aileron body.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] These balance weights are tear drop shaped (to reduce drag), which make them appear quite different from spades, although both project forward and below the aileron.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] In addition to reducing the risk of flutter, mass balances also reduce the stick forces required to move the control surface in maneuvers.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Used during aviation's pre-war "pioneer era" and into the early years of the First World War, these ailerons were each controlled by a single cable, which pulled the aileron up.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] When the aircraft was at rest, the ailerons hung vertically down.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This type of aileron was used on the Farman III biplane 1909 and the Short 166.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] A "reverse" version of this, utilizing wing-warping, existed on the later version of the Santos-Dumont *Demoiselle*, which only warped the wingtips "downward".
[src:airfoil/ailerons] One of the disadvantages of this setup was a greater tendency to yaw than even with basic interconnected ailerons.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] During the 1930s, a number of light aircraft used single acting controls but used springs to return the ailerons to their neutral positions when the stick was released.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The main problem with this type of aileron is the dangerous tendency to stall if used aggressively, especially if the aircraft is already in danger of stalling, hence the use primarily on prototypes, and their replacement on production aircraft with more conventional ailerons.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Engineer Leslie George Frise (1897–1979) of the Bristol Aeroplane Company developed an aileron shape that is pivoted at about its 25 to 30% chord line and near its bottom surface , in order to decrease stick forces as aircraft became faster during the 1930s.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] When the aileron is deflected up (to make its wing go down), the leading edge of the aileron starts to protrude below the underside of the wing into the airflow beneath the wing.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The moment of the leading edge in the airflow helps to move up the trailing edge, which decreases the stick force.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The down moving aileron also adds energy to the boundary layer.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The edge of the aileron directs air flow from the underside of the wing to the upper surface of the aileron, thus creating a lifting force added to the lift of the wing.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This reduces the needed deflection of the aileron.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Both the Canadian Fleet Model 2 biplane of 1930 and the 1938 popular US Piper J-3 Cub monoplane possessed Frise ailerons as designed and helped introduce them to a wide audience.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] A claimed benefit of the Frise aileron is the ability to counteract adverse yaw.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] To do so, the leading edge of the aileron has to be sharp or bluntly rounded, which adds significant drag to the upturned aileron and helps counterbalance the yaw force created by the other aileron turned down.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This can add some unpleasant, nonlinear effect and/or potentially dangerous aerodynamic vibration (flutter).
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Adverse yaw moment is basically countered by aircraft yaw stability and also by the use of differential aileron movement.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The Frise-type aileron also forms a slot, so air flows smoothly over the lowered aileron, making it more effective at high angles of attack.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Frise-type ailerons may also be designed to function differentially.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Like the differential aileron, the Frise-type aileron does not eliminate adverse yaw entirely.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Coordinated rudder application is still needed when ailerons are applied.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] By careful design of the mechanical linkages, the up aileron can be made to deflect more than the down aileron (e.g., US patent 1,565,097).
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This helps reduce the likelihood of a wing tip stall when aileron deflections are made at high angles of attack.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] In addition, the consequent differential in drag reduces adverse yaw (as also discussed above).
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The idea is that the loss of lift associated with the up aileron carries no penalty while the increase in lift associated with the down aileron is minimized.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The rolling couple on the aircraft is always the difference in lift between the two wings.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] A designer at de Havilland invented a simple and practical linkage and their de Havilland Tiger Moth classic British biplane became one of the best-known aircraft, and one of the earliest, to use differential ailerons.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] On the earliest Pioneer Era aircraft, such as the Wright Flyer and the later, 1909-origin Blériot XI and Etrich Taube, lateral control was effected by twisting the outboard portion of the wing so as to increase or decrease lift by changing the angle of attack.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This had the disadvantages of stressing the structure, being heavy on the controls, and of risking stalling the side with the increased angle of attack during a maneuver.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] By 1916, most designers had abandoned wing warping in favor of ailerons.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Researchers at NASA and elsewhere have been taking a second look at wing warping again, although under new names.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The NASA version is the X-53 Active Aeroelastic Wing while the United States Air Force tested the Adaptive Compliant Wing.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Spoilers are devices that when extended into the airflow over a wing, disrupt the airflow and reduce the amount of lift generated.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Many modern aircraft designs, especially jet aircraft, use spoilers in lieu of, or to supplement ailerons, such as the F4 Phantom II and Northrop P-61 Black Widow, which had almost full width flaps (there were very small conventional ailerons at the wingtips as well).
[src:airfoil/ailerons] All aircraft with dihedral have some form of yaw-roll coupling to promote stability.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Common trainers like the Cessna 152/172 series can be roll controlled with rudder alone.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] The rudder of the Boeing 737 has more roll authority over the aircraft than the ailerons at high angles of attack.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] This led to two notable accidents when the rudder jammed in the fully deflected position causing rollovers (see Boeing 737 rudder issues).
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Some aircraft such as the Fokker Spin and model gliders lack any type of lateral control.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Those aircraft use a higher amount of dihedral than conventional aircraft.
[src:airfoil/ailerons] Deflecting the rudder gives yaw and a lot of differential wing lift, giving a yaw induced roll moment.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The first 'heavier-than-air' air race was held on 23 May 1909 - the Prix de Lagatinerie, at the Port-Aviation aerodrome (often called "Juvisy Airfield") in Viry-Châtillon south of Paris, France.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Four pilots entered the race, two started, but nobody completed the full race distance; though this was not unexpected, as the rules specified that whoever travelled furthest would be the winner if no-one completed the race.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Léon Delagrange, who covered slightly more than half of the ten 1.2-kilometre (0.75 mi; 0.65 nmi) laps was declared the winner.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Some other minor events were held before the *Grande Semaine d'Aviation de la Champagne* in 22–29 August 1909 at Reims, France.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] This was the first major international flying event, drawing the most important aircraft makers and pilots of the era, as well as celebrities and royalty.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The premier event — the first Gordon Bennett Trophy competition — was won by Glenn Curtiss, who beat second-place finisher Louis Blériot by five seconds.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Curtiss was named 'Champion Air Racer of the World'.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The first air race in the United States was the 1910 Los Angeles International Air Meet at Dominguez Field, just south of Los Angeles, from 10 to 20 January 1910.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Roy Knabenshue and Charles Willard, who raised funding from railroad magnate Henry Huntington, and the Los Angeles Merchants and Manufacturers Association.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] William Randolph Hearst carried coverage of the event in his *Los Angeles Examiner*, and hired a hot air balloon with a promotional parse touting his newspaper.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The event attracted 43 entrants, of which 16 appeared.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] It was there that aviation pioneer and military pilot Jimmy Doolittle, then thirteen, saw his first airplane.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In the years before the First World War, popular interest in aviation led to a large number of air races in Europe; including the 1911 Circuit of Europe race, the Daily Mail Circuit of Britain Air Race, and the Aerial Derby.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 1913, the first Schneider Trophy seaplane race was held.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] When the competition was resumed after the war, it was significant in advancing aeroplane design, particularly in the fields of aerodynamics and engine design, and would show its results in the best fighters of World War II.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] On 19 October 1919, the Army Transcontinental Air Race began along a 2,700 mi (2,346 nmi; 4,345 km) route from Long Island, New York to San Francisco, California, and back, which would see widespread carnage; including seven fatalities (two en route to the race).
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Of the 48 aircraft that started, 33 would complete the double crossing of the continent.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 1921, the United States instituted the National Air Meets, which became the National Air Races in 1924.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 1929, the Women's Air Derby, nicknamed the 'Powder Puff Derby', became a part of the National Air Races circuit.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The National Air Races lasted until 1949.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The Cleveland Air Races was another important event.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 1947, an All-Woman Transcontinental Air Race, also dubbed the Powder Puff Derby was established, running until 1977.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 1934, the MacRobertson Air Race from England to Australia took place, with the winning de Havilland Comet flown by C.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] From 1934 until 1938, the Flight Around Latvia competition took place.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 1964, Bill Stead, a Nevada rancher, pilot, and unlimited hydroplane racing champion, organised the first Reno Air Races at a small dirt strip called the Sky Ranch, located between Sparks, Nevada, and Pyramid Lake.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The National Championship Air Races were soon moved to the Reno Stead Airport, and have been held there every September since 1966.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The five-day event attracts around 200,000 people, and includes racing around courses marked out by pylons for six classes of aircraft: Unlimited, Formula One, Sport Biplane, AT-6, Sport, and Jet.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] It also features civil airshow acts, military flight demonstrations, and a large static aircraft display.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Numerous other venues across the United States, Canada, and Mexico have also hosted events featuring the smaller Formula One and Biplane classes.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 1970, American Formula One racing was exported to Europe (Great Britain, and then to France), where almost as many races have been held as in the U.S.A.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Also in 1970, the California 1000 Air Race started at the Mojave Airport with a 66 lap unlimited air race that featured a Douglas DC-7, with one aircraft completing the circuit.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 2003, Red Bull created a series called the Red Bull Air Race World Championship, in which competitors flew individually between pairs of pylons, while performing prescribed manoeuvres.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Usually held over water near large cities, the sport has attracted large crowds and renewed media interest in air racing.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The inaugural season had stops in Austria and Hungary.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 2019, Red Bull decided not to continue the Red Bull Air Race World Championship.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Aero GP has multiple aircraft racing together pik around pylons, and is based in Europe where it has held an air race each year since 2005.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In June 2005 against all odds and extreme pressure from the Reno Air Race Association not to start another race, entrepreneur Jeff Landers, a Memphis native, organized the Tunica Air Races in Tunica, Mississippi with Unlimited, T-6, and Sport classes represented.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] After the successful and safe race in 2005 RARA fought any and all efforts for the growth of this motorsport and any effort for a 2006 race there and one in Tucson Arizona.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Powered paragliding or paramotor races have been organised by the Parabatix Sky Racers made up of the world's top paramotor pilots.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The first occurring on 4 September 2010 in an airfield in Montauban, Southern France.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] These are foot-launched ram-air wings powered by small two-stroke engines, and allow for much smaller race venues such as city parks or beaches, where the audience can see the pilots up close as they carry out spectacular manoeuvres swooping close to the ground-pylons during the race.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In November 2021, the first remotely-piloted eVTOL drag race between two Airspeeder craft took place.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] In 2022, The remotely-piloted racing series (Airspeeder EXA Series) began in 2022 with Zephatali Walsh named as the inaugural season champion.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] The aircraft, built by Alauda Aeronautics, use electric vertical take-off and landing (eVTOL) technology and are designed to be crewed by human pilots.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Restricting aircraft to a specific type or design creates a competition that focuses on pilot skill.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Air racing events such as the Reno air races, incorporate multiple classes or aircraft.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] These may be defined by the race organiser, or by a sanctioned group.
[src:airfoil/air-racing] Some air races are limited to a single class.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] An **airfoil** (American English) or **aerofoil** (British English) is a streamlined body that is capable of generating significantly more lift than drag.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Wings, sails and propeller blades are examples of airfoils.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Foils which work in a similar way submerged in water are called hydrofoils.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] When oriented at a suitable angle, a solid body moving through a fluid deflects the passing fluid, resulting in a force on the airfoil in the direction opposite to the deflection.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] This force is known as an aerodynamic force and can be resolved into two components: lift (perpendicular to the freestream velocity) and drag (parallel to the freestream velocity).
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The lift on an airfoil is primarily the result of its angle of attack.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Most foil shapes require a positive angle of attack to generate lift, but cambered airfoils can generate lift at zero angle of attack.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Airfoils have different shapes for different speeds: those for subsonic flight have a rounded leading edge, while those for supersonic flight tend to be slimmer.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The deflection of air by an airfoil generates a lower-pressure region above and behind itself.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] This pressure difference is accompanied by a velocity difference, as explained by Bernoulli's principle, so the resulting flowfield about the airfoil has a higher average velocity on the upper surface than on the lower surface.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] In some situations (e.g., inviscid potential flow) the lift force can be related directly to the average top/bottom velocity difference without computing the pressure by using the concept of circulation and the Kutta–Joukowski theorem.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The wings and stabilizers of fixed-wing aircraft, as well as helicopter rotor blades, are built with airfoil-shaped cross sections.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Airfoils are also found in propellers, fans, compressors and turbines.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Sails are also airfoils, and the underwater surfaces of sailboats, such as the centerboard, rudder, and keel, are similar in cross-section and operate on the same principles as airfoils.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Swimming and flying creatures and even many plants and sessile organisms employ airfoils/hydrofoils, common examples being bird wings, the bodies of fish, and the shape of sand dollars.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] An airfoil-shaped wing can create downforce on an automobile or other motor vehicle, improving traction.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] When the wind is obstructed by an object such as a flat plate, a building, or the deck of a bridge, the object will experience drag and also an aerodynamic force perpendicular to the wind.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] This does not mean the object qualifies as an airfoil.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Airfoils are highly-efficient lifting shapes, able to generate more lift than similarly sized flat plates of the same area, and able to generate lift with significantly less drag.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Airfoils are used in the design of aircraft, propellers, rotor blades, wind turbines and other applications of aeronautical engineering.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] A lift and drag curve obtained in wind tunnel testing is shown on the right.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The curve represents an airfoil with a positive camber so some lift is produced at zero angle of attack.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] With increased angle of attack, lift increases in a roughly linear relation, called the *slope* of the lift curve.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] At about 18 degrees this airfoil stalls, and lift falls off quickly beyond that.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The drop in lift can be explained by the action of the upper-surface boundary layer, which separates and greatly thickens over the upper surface at and past the stall angle.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The thickened boundary layer's displacement thickness changes the airfoil's effective shape, in particular it reduces its effective camber, which modifies the overall flow field so as to reduce the circulation and the lift.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The thicker boundary layer also causes a large increase in pressure drag, so that the overall drag increases sharply near and past the stall point.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Airfoil design is a major facet of aerodynamics.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Various airfoils serve different flight regimes.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Asymmetric airfoils can generate lift at zero angle of attack, while a symmetric airfoil may better suit frequent inverted flight as in an aerobatic airplane.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] In the region of the ailerons and near a wingtip a symmetric airfoil can be used to increase the range of angles of attack to avoid spin–stall.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Thus a large range of angles can be used without boundary layer separation.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Subsonic airfoils have a round leading edge, which is naturally insensitive to the angle of attack.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The cross section is not strictly circular, however: the radius of curvature is increased before the wing achieves maximum thickness to minimize the chance of boundary layer separation.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] This elongates the wing and moves the point of maximum thickness back from the leading edge.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Supersonic airfoils are much more angular in shape and can have a very sharp leading edge, which is very sensitive to angle of attack.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] A supercritical airfoil has its maximum thickness close to the leading edge to have a lot of length to slowly shock the supersonic flow back to subsonic speeds.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Generally such transonic airfoils and also the supersonic airfoils have a low camber to reduce drag divergence.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Modern aircraft wings may have different airfoil sections along the wing span, each one optimized for the conditions in each section of the wing.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Movable high-lift devices, flaps and sometimes slats, are fitted to airfoils on almost every aircraft.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] A trailing edge flap acts similarly to an aileron; however, it, as opposed to an aileron, can be retracted partially into the wing if not used.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] For many wings, the boundary layer of the air flow close to the upper surface rapidly becomes turbulent past the maximum thickness point, which increases the skin friction drag.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] A **laminar flow wing** moves the maximum thickness point well back along the chord from a typical 25% chord position from to 60% from the leading edge or more.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] This maintains smooth laminar flow over a larger percentage of the wing and significantly reduces drag.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] However, surface contamination will disrupt the boundary layer, making it turbulent.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Insects, for example, impacting and sticking onto the wing will cause the loss of wedge shaped regions of laminar flow across the wing's surface.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] This is a particular problem for aircraft with high take off speeds, since many insects are found near the ground making it unlikely that laminar flow can be sustained into the flight.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Gliders have seen widespread uptake of laminar flow airfoils due to their low speeds and need for low drag aerodynamic structures.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] NASA's research in the 1980s revealed the practicality and usefulness of laminar flow wing designs and opened the way for laminar-flow applications on modern practical aircraft surfaces, from subsonic general aviation aircraft to transonic large transport aircraft, to supersonic designs.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Schemes have been devised to define airfoils – an example is the NACA system.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Various airfoil generation systems are also used.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] An example of a general purpose airfoil that finds wide application, and pre–dates the NACA system, is the Clark-Y.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Today, airfoils can be designed for specific functions by the use of computer programs.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Some important parameters to describe an airfoil's shape are its *camber* and its *thickness*.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] For example, an airfoil of the NACA 4-digit series such as the NACA 2415 (to be read as 2 – 4 – 15) describes an airfoil with a camber of 0.02 chord located at 0.40 chord, with 0.15 chord of maximum thickness.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] In two-dimensional flow around a uniform wing of infinite span, the slope of the lift curve is determined primarily by the *trailing edge angle*.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The slope is greatest if the angle is zero; and decreases as the angle increases.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] For a wing of finite span, the aspect ratio of the wing also significantly influences the slope of the curve.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] As aspect ratio decreases, the slope also decreases.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] 2. on a cambered airfoil, the aerodynamic center lies exactly one quarter of the chord behind the leading edge, but the position of the center of pressure moves when the angle of attack changes.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] 3. the slope of the *lift coefficient versus angle of attack* line is $2\pi \!$ units per radian.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] is the section lift coefficient when the angle of attack is zero.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Thin airfoil theory assumes the air is an inviscid fluid so does not account for the stall of the airfoil, which usually occurs at an angle of attack between 10° and 15° for typical airfoils.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] In the mid-late 2000s, however, a theory predicting the onset of leading-edge stall was proposed by Wallace J.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Morris's subsequent refinements contain the details on the current state of theoretical knowledge on the leading-edge stall phenomenon.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Morris's theory predicts the critical angle of attack for leading-edge stall onset as the condition at which a global separation zone is predicted in the solution for the inner flow.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Morris's theory demonstrates that a subsonic flow about a thin airfoil can be described in terms of an outer region, around most of the airfoil chord, and an inner region, around the nose, that asymptotically match each other.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] As the flow in the outer region is dominated by classical thin airfoil theory, Morris's equations exhibit many components of thin airfoil theory.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] In thin airfoil theory, the width of the (2D) airfoil is assumed negligible, and the airfoil itself replaced with a 1D blade along its camber line, oriented at the angle of attack α.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Let the position along the blade be x, ranging from 0 at the wing's front to c at the trailing edge; the camber of the airfoil, *dy*⁄*dx*, is assumed sufficiently small that one need not distinguish between x and position relative to the fuselage.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The flow across the airfoil generates a circulation around the blade, which can be modeled as a vortex sheet of position-varying strength γ(*x*).
[src:airfoil/airfoil] The Kutta condition implies that γ(*c*)=0, but the strength is singular at the bladefront, with γ(*x*)∝1⁄√*x* for *x* ≈ 0.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] From the Biot–Savart law, the vorticity γ(*x*) produces a flow field $w(x)={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{0}^{c}{\frac {\gamma (x')}{x-x'}}\,dx'{\text{,}}$ oriented normal to the airfoil at x.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] Since the airfoil is an impermeable surface, the flow $w(x)$ must balance an inverse flow from V.
[src:airfoil/airfoil] By the small-angle approximation, V is inclined at angle α-*dy*⁄*dx* relative to the blade at position x, and the normal component is correspondingly (α-*dy*⁄*dx*)*V*.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Varieties of American English include many patterns of pronunciation, vocabulary, grammar, and particularly spelling that are unified nationwide but distinct from other forms of English around the world.
[src:airfoil/american-english] However, historical and present linguistic evidence does not support the notion of there being one single mainstream American accent.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The sound of American English continues to evolve, with some local accents disappearing, but several larger regional accents having emerged in the 20th century.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The use of English in the United States is a result of British colonization of the Americas.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The first wave of English-speaking settlers arrived in North America during the early 17th century, followed by further migrations in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:airfoil/american-english] English thus predominated in the colonies even by the end of the 17th century's first immigration of non-English speakers from Western Europe and Africa.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Firsthand descriptions of a fairly uniform American English (particularly in contrast to the diverse regional dialects of British English) became common after the mid-18th century, while at the same time speakers' identification with this new variety increased.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Since the 18th century, American English has developed into some new varieties, including regional dialects that retain minor influences from waves of immigrant speakers of diverse languages, primarily European languages.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Some racial and regional variation in American English reflects these groups' patterns of geographic settlement, segregation, and resettlement.
[src:airfoil/american-english] This can be seen, for example, in the influence of 18th-century Protestant Ulster Scots immigrants (known in the U.S. as the Scotch-Irish) in Appalachia developing Appalachian English and the 20th-century Great Migration bringing African-American Vernacular English to the Great Lakes urban centers.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Most American English accents fall under an umbrella known as General American.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Rather than one particular accent, General American is a spectrum of those American accents that Americans themselves do not associate with some particular region, ethnicity, or socioeconomic group.
[src:airfoil/american-english] General American features are used most by Americans in formal contexts or who are highly educated.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Regional accents whose native features are perceived as General American include the accents of the North Midland (parts of the Midwest), Western New England, and the West.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The General American sound system's scope of influence and degree of expansion has been debated by linguists since the term was first used roughly a century ago.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Many late-20th and early-21st century studies are showing that it is gradually ousting the regional accents in urban areas of the South and the interior North, New York City, Philadelphia, and many other areas.
[src:airfoil/american-english] It can generally be said that younger Americans are avoiding their traditional local features in favor of this more nationwide norm.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Furthermore, even General American itself appears to be evolving, with linguists identifying new features in speakers born since the last quarter of the 20th century, like a merger of the low-back vowels and a potentially related vowel shift, that are spreading across the nation.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Like many British accents, T glottalization is the norm in American accents, though only in particular environments (with *satin* pronounced [ˈsæʔn̩], not [ˈsætn̩]).
[src:airfoil/american-english] Specifically, the LOT–PALM merger is complete among most Americans and the LOT–THOUGHT merger among roughly half.
[src:airfoil/american-english] A three-way LOT–PALM–THOUGHT merger is also very common, meaning that words like *baht*, *bot*, and *bought* are all homophones.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Most Americans pronounce the diphthong /aɪ/ before a voiceless consonant different from that same vowel before a voiced consonant: thus, in *price* and *bright* versus in *prize* and *bride*.
[src:airfoil/american-english] For many, outside the South, the first element of the diphthong is a higher and shorter vowel sound when in pre-voiceless position as opposed to pre-voiced position.
[src:airfoil/american-english] All of these phenomena are explained in further detail under General American.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Unlike American accents, the traditional standard accent of (southern) England has evolved a *trap–bath* split.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Moreover, American accents preserve /h/ at the start of syllables, while perhaps a majority of the regional dialects of England participate in /h/ dropping, particularly in informal contexts.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The process of developing new lexical items began as soon as British English-speaking colonists in North America began borrowing names for unfamiliar flora, fauna, and topography from the Native American languages.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Examples of such names are *opossum, raccoon, squash*, *moose* (from Algonquian), *wigwam*, and *moccasin*.
[src:airfoil/american-english] American English speakers have integrated traditionally non-English terms and expressions into the mainstream cultural lexicon; for instance, *en masse*, from French; *cookie*, from Dutch; *kindergarten* from German, and *rodeo* from Spanish.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Landscape features are often loanwords from French or Spanish, and the word *corn*, used in England to refer to wheat (or any cereal), came to denote the maize plant, the most important crop in the U.S.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Other common differences between UK and American English include: *aerial* (UK) vs.
[src:airfoil/american-english] *apartment*, *fringe* (UK; for hair hanging over the forehead) vs.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Most Mexican Spanish contributions came after the War of 1812, with the opening of the West, like *ranch* (now a common house style).
[src:airfoil/american-english] Due to Mexican culinary influence, many Spanish words are incorporated in general use when talking about certain popular dishes: cilantro (instead of coriander), queso, tacos, quesadillas, enchiladas, tostadas, fajitas, burritos, and guacamole.
[src:airfoil/american-english] These words usually lack an English equivalent and are found in popular restaurants.
[src:airfoil/american-english] New forms of dwelling created new terms *(lot, waterfront)* and types of homes like *log cabin, adobe* in the 18th century; *apartment, shanty* in the 19th century; *project, condominium, townhouse, mobile home* in the 20th century; and parts thereof *(driveway, breezeway, backyard)*.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Already existing English words—such as *store, shop, lumber*—underwent shifts in meaning; others remained in the U.S. while changing in Britain.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Science, urbanization, and democracy have been important factors in bringing about changes in the written and spoken language of the United States.
[src:airfoil/american-english] From the world of business and finance came new terms (*merger, downsize, bottom line*), from sports and gambling terminology came, specific jargon aside, common everyday American idioms, including many idioms related to baseball.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The names of some American inventions remained largely confined to North America (*elevator* [except in the aeronautical sense], *gasoline*) as did certain automotive terms (*truck*, *trunk*).
[src:airfoil/american-english] New foreign loanwords came with 19th and early 20th century European immigration to the U.S.; notably, from Yiddish *(chutzpah, schmooze, bupkis, glitch*) and German (*hamburger, wiener*).
[src:airfoil/american-english] American English has always shown a marked tendency to use words in different parts of speech and nouns are often used as verbs.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Examples of nouns that are now also verbs are *interview, advocate, vacuum, lobby, pressure, rear-end, transition, feature, profile, hashtag, head, divorce, loan, estimate, X-ray, spearhead, skyrocket, showcase, bad-mouth, vacation, major,* and many others.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Compounds coined in the U.S. are for instance *foothill, landslide* (in all senses), *backdrop, teenager,* *brainstorm, bandwagon, hitchhike, smalltime,* and a huge number of others.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Other compound words have been founded based on industrialization and the wave of the automobile: five-passenger car, four-door sedan, two-door sedan, and station-wagon (called an estate car in British English).
[src:airfoil/american-english] Some are euphemistic *(human resources, affirmative action, correctional facility).* Many compound nouns have the verb-and-preposition combination: *stopover, lineup, tryout, spin-off, shootout, holdup, hideout, comeback, makeover,* and many more.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Some prepositional and phrasal verbs are in fact of American origin (*win out, hold up, back up/off/down/out, face up to* and many others).
[src:airfoil/american-english] Noun endings such as *-ee (retiree), -ery (bakery), -ster (gangster)* and *-cian (beautician)* are also particularly productive in the U.S.
[src:airfoil/american-english] A number of words and meanings that originated in Middle English or Early Modern English and that have been in everyday use in the United States have since disappeared in most varieties of British English; some of these have cognates in Lowland Scots.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Terms such as *fall* ("autumn"), *faucet* ("tap"), *diaper* ("nappy"; itself unused in the U.S.), *candy* ("sweets"), *skillet*, *eyeglasses*, and *obligate* are often regarded as Americanisms.
[src:airfoil/american-english] *Fall*, however, came to denote the season in 16th century England, a contraction of Middle English expressions like "fall of the leaf" and "fall of the year".
[src:airfoil/american-english] *Gotten* (past participle of *get*) is often considered to be largely an Americanism.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Other words and meanings were brought back to Britain from the U.S., especially in the second half of the 20th century; these include *hire* ("to employ"), *I guess* (famously criticized by H.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Fowler), *baggage*, *hit* (a place), and the adverbs *overly* and *presently* ("currently").
[src:airfoil/american-english] Some of these, for example, *monkey wrench* and *wastebasket*, originated in 19th century Britain.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The adjectives *mad* meaning "angry", *smart* meaning "intelligent", and *sick* meaning "ill" are also more frequent in American (and Irish) English than British English.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Linguist Bert Vaux created a survey, completed in 2003, polling English speakers across the United States about their specific everyday word choices, hoping to identify regionalisms.
[src:airfoil/american-english] American English and British English (BrE) differ in relatively minor ways in their grammar and writing conventions.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The first large American dictionary, *An American Dictionary of the English Language*, known as Webster's Dictionary, was written by Noah Webster in 1828, codifying several of these spellings.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Often, these differences are a matter of relative preferences rather than absolute rules; and most are not stable since the two varieties are constantly influencing each other, and American English is not a standardized set of dialects.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Differences in orthography are also minor.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The main differences are that American English usually uses spellings such as *flavor* for British *flavour*, *fiber* for *fibre*, *defense* for *defence*, *analyze* for *analyse*, *license* for *licence*, *catalog* for *catalogue* and *traveling* for *travelling*.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Noah Webster popularized such spellings in America, but he did not invent most of them.
[src:airfoil/american-english] AmE almost always uses *-ize* in words like *realize*.
[src:airfoil/american-english] BrE prefers *-ise*, but also uses *-ize* on occasion (see: Oxford spelling).
[src:airfoil/american-english] There are a few differences in punctuation rules.
[src:airfoil/american-english] British English is more tolerant of run-on sentences, called "comma splices" in American English, and American English prefers that periods and commas be placed inside closing quotation marks even in cases in which British rules would place them outside.
[src:airfoil/american-english] American English also favors the double quotation mark ("like this") over the single ('as here').
[src:airfoil/american-english] AmE sometimes favors words that are morphologically more complex, whereas BrE uses clipped forms, such as AmE *transportation* and BrE *transport* or where the British form is a back-formation, such as AmE *burglarize* and BrE *burgle* (from *burglar*).
[src:airfoil/american-english] However, while individuals usually use one or the other, both forms will be widely understood and mostly used alongside each other within the two systems.
[src:airfoil/american-english] as well as the related Telsur Project's regional maps.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Any region may also contain speakers of a "General American" accent that resists the marked features of their region.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The regional sounds of present-day American English are reportedly engaged in a complex phenomenon of "both convergence and divergence": some accents are homogenizing and leveling, while others are diversifying and deviating further away from one another.
[src:airfoil/american-english] As of the 20th century, the middle and eastern Great Lakes area, Chicago being the largest city with these speakers, also ushered in certain unique features, including the fronting of the LOT /ɑ/ vowel in the mouth toward [a] and tensing of the TRAP /æ/ vowel wholesale to [eə].
[src:airfoil/american-english] These sound changes have triggered a series of other vowel shifts in the same region, known by linguists as the "Inland North".
[src:airfoil/american-english] The Inland North shares with the Eastern New England dialect (including Boston accents) a backer tongue positioning of the GOOSE /u/ vowel (to [u]) and the MOUTH /aʊ/ vowel (to [ɑʊ~äʊ]) in comparison to the rest of the country.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Ranging from northern New England across the Great Lakes to Minnesota, another Northern regional marker is the variable fronting of /ɑ/ before /r/, for example, appearing four times in the stereotypical Boston shibboleth *Park the car in Harvard Yard*.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Several other phenomena serve to distinguish regional American accents.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Boston, Pittsburgh, Upper Midwestern, and Western U.S. accents have fully completed a merger of the LOT vowel with the THOUGHT vowel (/ɑ/ and /ɔ/, respectively): a *cot–caught* merger, which is rapidly spreading throughout the whole country.
[src:airfoil/american-english] However, the South, Inland North, and a Northeastern coastal corridor passing through Rhode Island, New York City, Philadelphia, and Baltimore typically preserve an older *cot–caught* distinction.
[src:airfoil/american-english] For that Northeastern corridor, the realization of the THOUGHT vowel is particularly marked, as depicted in humorous spellings, like in *tawk* and *cawfee* (*talk* and *coffee*), which intend to represent it being tense and diphthongal: [oə].
[src:airfoil/american-english] A split of TRAP into two separate phonemes, using different *a* pronunciations for example in *gap* [æ] versus *gas* [eə], further defines New York City as well as Philadelphia–Baltimore accents.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Most Americans preserve all historical /r/ sounds, using what is known as a rhotic accent.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Non-rhoticity makes a word like *car* sound like *cah* or *source* like *sauce*.
[src:airfoil/american-english] New York City and Southern accents are the most widely recognized regional accents in the country, as well as the most stigmatized and socially disfavored.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The fronting of the vowels of GOOSE, GOAT, MOUTH, and STRUT tends to also define Southern accents as well as the accents spoken in the "Midland": a vast band of the country that constitutes an intermediate dialect region between the traditional North and South.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Western U.S. accents mostly fall under the General American spectrum.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Although no longer region-specific, African-American Vernacular English, which remains the native variety of most working- and middle-class African Americans, has a close relationship to Southern dialects and has greatly influenced everyday speech of many Americans, including hip hop culture.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Hispanic and Latino Americans have also developed native-speaker varieties of English.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The best-studied Latino Englishes are Chicano English, spoken in the West and Midwest, and New York Latino English, spoken in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Additionally, ethnic varieties such as Yeshiva English and "Yinglish" are spoken by some American Orthodox Jews, Cajun Vernacular English by some Cajuns in southern Louisiana, and Pennsylvania Dutch English by some Pennsylvania Dutch people.
[src:airfoil/american-english] American Indian Englishes have been documented among diverse Indian tribes.
[src:airfoil/american-english] The island state of Hawaii, though primarily English-speaking, is also home to a creole language known commonly as Hawaiian Pidgin, and some Hawaii residents speak English with a Pidgin-influenced accent.
[src:airfoil/american-english] In 2024, about 247.7 million Americans, aged five or above, spoke English at home, a majority (77%) of the total U.S. population aged five and over.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Of the 50 states, 32 have adopted legislation granting official (or co-official) status to English within their jurisdictions, in some cases as part of what has been called the English-only movement.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Typically only "English" is specified, not a particular variety like American English.
[src:airfoil/american-english] Puerto Rico is the only United States territory in which another language – Spanish – is the common language at home, in public, and in government.
